I'm planning on pursuing an education in social work with the ultimate goal of joining the Division of Family and Children Services to help kids who've been through abuse or neglect, as well as offer support to troubled families. When it comes to social work, I'm all about bringing the following core values to the table: service, respect, an honest approach, and dedication to making relationships between people better, along with constantly working on myself to stay sharp in my field. These values aren't just important for social workers; they're super important to me personally.

I've always had a desire to help others, but I wasn't sure what career path I wanted to take. Throughout high school and college, I saw a lot of people trying to run away from their problems instead of facing them, and some turned to not-so-great coping mechanisms. Because of what I've seen, I decided to major in Psychology. Still unsure about my career path, I took a break after I graduated from Piedmont College in 2009. One summer, a friend introduced me to a sixteen-year-old who was really nervous because he was staying with her – he was trying to escape his abusive parents. The next day, I found out that he'd called the police to their house. I went over to their place and talked to the police about my concerns, explaining that I'd just graduated from Piedmont College with a degree in Psychology. They asked me to talk to the parents since there wasn't much they could do. When I questioned them, they seemed really nervous and made excuses for their son's behavior, saying he was just trying to get people involved in "simple" family disputes. That experience made me seriously consider a career in social work to help kids deal with similar problems.

I'm also really passionate about social justice. Society says that the individual is important, but we end up trying to be like everyone else instead of embracing our uniqueness. I'm all about being an individual and not limiting myself to what others think I should be. Throughout high school and college, I protested against social injustice in any way I could: I'd dye my hair weird colors, wear clothes that fit my style, get piercings that went against the norm, and speak out against racism and discrimination whenever I saw it. I believe in social justice, and I'll keep speaking out against it.

This paper explores the connection between the Biological and Sociocultural models and insomnia. The Biological model focuses on the genetic information passed down from our parents and medical aspects, while the Sociocultural model looks at the impact of environment on sleep, including things like where you live, your race, ethnicity, and income level. To understand these models, we'll look at various studies that relate to them and use them to explain each one better. We'll also critique the research to point out its strengths and weaknesses.

Insomnia can be broken down into three categories: primary sleep disorders, sleep disorders that are connected to other mental health issues, and sleep disorders caused by medical problems or substances. The primary sleep disorders are Dyssonmias, which are problems with falling asleep or staying asleep, and Parasomnias, which are sleep disorders that cause weird behaviors or physical things to happen while you're asleep. The Dyssonmias include Primary Insomnia, where you can't fall asleep or stay asleep, Primary Hypersomnia, where you can't stay awake, Narcolepsy, which involves extreme sleepiness and hallucinations, and a few others. The Parasomnias include Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, and Sleepwalking Disorder.

The sleep disorders connected to other mental health issues are related to Axis I or Axis II disorders. The Biological and Sociocultural models are especially useful for understanding the primary sleep disorders. Research on the Biological model has found that the hypothalamus in our brain has special cells that control our sleep-wake cycle. Scientists have done studies with mice and found that these cells have something called orexin, which helps us stay awake or fall asleep. They've also found that a receptor called GABAB is responsible for sleep and wakefulness. When this receptor is activated, it helps us fall asleep, and when it's not working right, it can cause problems with sleep. A study using a special medication called baclofen found that it can help people sleep better by activating the GABAB receptor. This shows that there's a link between our genes and our ability to sleep. This has sociocultural implications, because if we inherit a problem with the GABAB receptor, it could affect our sleep and make it hard for us to focus on everyday tasks.

This paper is about Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), which is a pretty complex topic. So, to start, let's break it down: CAPD is basically how well the brain uses the sounds it hears. It's a weird way to put it, but essentially, the brain can't process what we hear in a normal way. People with CAPD can hear just fine, but it's like their brain's sound-decoding skills are a bit wonky. It's not about not being able to hear, it's about how the brain takes what we hear and turns it into something that makes sense.

CAPD has been around since the 1950s, when researchers first started noticing that some kids with speech problems had trouble processing sounds. A team of Italian researchers, Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari, started working on tests for these kids in 1954, and in 1961, a researcher named Kimura came up with a way to understand how the brain handles sounds. This all led to a big conference in 1977 that got more people interested in studying CAPD.

CAPD can show up in a bunch of different ways: someone with CAPD might have trouble pinpointing where sounds are coming from, or might get confused when there are multiple sounds happening at once. They might also struggle to recognize patterns in sounds, or tell when someone's being sarcastic, or block out one sound if another sound comes after it. It's like their brain's sound-sorting system is a bit messed up. They might also have trouble making sense of sounds in a way that they can use them in real life, or figuring out the order of sounds.

So, to figure out if someone has CAPD, doctors and specialists use a bunch of different tests to see how they respond to sounds. This can include watching how they behave when they're listening, or asking them questions and seeing how they react. There's no single test that's super reliable, and nobody really knows what causes CAPD. The tests usually involve playing a bunch of sounds at the same time and asking the person to pick out specific ones, or recording the sounds in their ear and seeing how their brain responds.

Twelfth Night makes it clear that even though pretending to be someone else can get you out of a tight spot, eventually you're going to have to stop or risk losing yourself forever. The problem with giving up the act is that you might end up all alone, cut off from the people around you. It's a tough choice - do you take care of yourself or do you take care of the people you care about? Some people might not even get mad if they figure out you've been lying, but others will definitely be super ticked off.

The whole idea of dressing up as the opposite sex gets even more complicated because it makes you wonder why anyone would want to change who they are in the first place. Like, why would Viola pretend to be a guy to protect herself from bad people? She says, "I'll meet a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count..." (5.1.247-249) She has to pretend to be a guy because she's in a new place and doesn't want to get hurt. But by doing that, she ends up losing her support system and even makes people think she's a different person, like Sebastian. Olivia totally falls for her, and Viola also has to deal with some weird feelings for Orsino. "Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay." (5.1.138) It's all pretty weird.

Some people might see Twelfth Night as a way to explore how pretending to be someone else can help you figure out your true feelings. Like, Olivia and Orsino might be hiding something, and Viola's disguise is like a wake-up call for them. The way they react to Viola makes you wonder if they were really attracted to her as a guy or if they were just freaked out by their own feelings. It's like Shakespeare is poking fun at people who judge others based on how they look. Olivia is totally shallow, because she goes from loving Cesario to loving Sebastian without even a second thought, and then just thinks of Viola as a sister. "A sister, you are she." (5.1.315)

The German colonial empire was known for its brutality, especially in the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. However, describing it as just that doesn't do it justice. The empire was all over the map in terms of policies and ruling styles, like its geography. Different colonies had different approaches to education too. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found that the locals were already pretty educated and literate. German education efforts in Kamerun and other colonies got some positive reviews from the time.

But German South West Africa (present-day Namibia) was a whole different story. Unlike East Africa, where the government set up schools and was really involved in teaching the locals, they pretty much left education to missionary groups who didn't get a lot of support from the government. The government did invest in educating Europeans living there, though - they set up their own schools and really helped out the missionary schools. These decisions had a lasting impact on South West Africa, even after the Germans were gone. While other German colonies had a lot of educated Africans, in South West Africa, the majority of the population was basically uneducated and illiterate. It's not like one single thing caused this difference, though - it was a bunch of social, political, and economic factors that made South West Africa's experience unique.

There's actually a lot of research out there about education in the German colonies, but most of it is in German and was written a long time ago. Early studies were mainly just describing the educational systems in each colony. Later studies in English did some cool comparisons between different colonies and really dug deep into the details. One of the most important studies on this topic is Cohen's work on education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen looked at how the two colonies were similar and different and figured out some of the reasons behind those differences. According to Cohen, the fact that there were so many settlers in South West Africa explains a lot about the colony's educational system.

South West Africa had a pretty good climate, considering it's mostly desert, so there were a lot of Europeans living there by 1913 - almost 15,000, which is way more than in East Africa. The settlers in South West Africa were actually pretty lucky to be living in a place with a relatively nice climate.

Heavy Metal music has evolved a ton over the past century, and it's hard to even try to list all the genres. To make things even more complicated, most of these genres have spawned sub and sub-sub genres. It's crazy to think about how far it's come, especially considering that the sub-genre of Heavy Metal has become one of the most diverse and expressive genres in the past 40 years. This is because it shows a wide range of emotions, although they tend to lean towards the darker side. People started to realize that Heavy Metal had real flexibility and took advantage of it to create their own sub-genre, followed by sub-sub-genres, and it just keeps going.

Nowadays, we're at a point where there are so many niches of groups that it's hard to figure out what Heavy Metal even is. It's incorporated so many themes from other genres, but it all started somewhere. To understand the Metal music that's everywhere today, you gotta know what the Metal movement is and why it's a movement, not just a genre.

Heavy Metal is basically a movement defined by darkness. It's like, more of everything - more bass, more volume, more violence, more theatrics. It's way less about being raw and basic; in Metal bands, people are super skilled at playing their instruments, and that comes through in the music. Plus, Metal is a movement that's super influenced by drugs - the psychedelic boom in the '70s got people pretty wild, and that's when some of the craziest, otherworldly records started coming out. It's got all these dark, visceral qualities that were new to the music scene because most popular music was all about being happy and light. Later generations of Metal took some of their influence from the dark, visceral qualities of the Romantic Era. Some lyrics, like these from Helter Skelter, show just how dark Metal can get. It's like the Beatles' darker side, all about ups and downs, kinda like being on drugs. Some people even consider this song to be one of the first Heavy Metal songs ever. It was a response to the Rolling Stones, who were also getting darker and heavier with their music. The Beatles wanted to prove they could be just as heavy, so they put this song on The White Album.

It's pretty cool to think that before the Surrealists were making their dreamy art, Henri Rousseau was actually living his own dream, both literally and figuratively. The Dream, a painting he made in 1910, shows a woman who's in awe of the cool stuff she's seeing in her dreamland, but it also represents Rousseau's own goals as an artist. He had been hoping to get recognized by other artists and art lovers for a long time, but he was stuck with a weird problem: should he try to fit in with the art world by copying other artists, or be true to himself and do his own thing? The Dream is like his masterpiece that shows how he struggled with this for his whole career – wanting to be accepted by the art world he loved, but also wanting to be different and make his own unique art.

To really get what The Dream is all about, you gotta know a bit about Rousseau's life. He was born on May 21, 1844, in a small town in northwest France. His dad was a tinsmith who was pretty successful, but Rousseau never got any formal art training – he just worked a regular job until he was 40. People even started calling him a customs inspector, but that's not what he really did (Shattuck 46). When his first wife, Clémence, died, along with eight of their babies, Rousseau was left with a ton of grief and a young daughter, Julia. He started painting to help him deal with the pain and move on. Unlike some other artists of his time, Rousseau wasn't all about painting the perfect peasant scene – he was just a regular guy with regular hopes and dreams.

It's not hard to see why Rousseau wanted to fit in with the art world – he was starting from scratch, and he was working with some really talented artists who were already famous. He didn't get recognized until around the same time that Matisse was making a name for himself. As author Jan Gordon pointed out in his book Modern French Painters, Rousseau and Matisse were different in a lot of ways – not just in their art style, but also why they made art in the first place. While Matisse was all about not being boring, Rousseau just wanted to make art that was good enough to get him into the Artiste Français (Gordon 92).

You know, people have been saying for ages that there's a deep connection between how we think about right and wrong, and how we think about what's beautiful and what's not. I'm convinced that there's a reason for this. As John Keats so wisely put it in his "Ode on a Grecian Urn", "Beauty is truth, truth beauty - That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." Most of what we learn in life comes from school or through our experiences, but somehow, we naturally know what's beautiful and what's the right thing to do, even if no one taught us. Both ethics and aesthetics are all about explaining why something is beautiful or right, rather than telling us how to decide what's good art or good behavior. 

In other words, when we talk about why we like a particular painting, or why we think a certain action is the right thing to do, we can't really put our finger on it. A conversation about the Mona Lisa might go on and on about its lighting or the culture behind it, but ultimately, that doesn't capture what makes it so great. When someone asks you about your favorite book or piece of art, you often end up saying "There's just something about it" before trying to come up with a more thoughtful explanation. I think that both art and morality have this quality to them - they can't be fully explained by just listing their good qualities. As Flannery O'Connor said, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way... you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate." Even if we try to describe a book in detail, there's something more to it that we can't quite put into words. I think that this is true for ethics too - as Ludwig Wittgenstein said, "It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental." I think that this "something" - this intangible quality - is what makes art and morality so powerful, and that it's what connects them.

I believe that ethics and art are closely related because we experience them in a way that's hard to explain. They affect us on a deep level, but we can't quite put into words. This connection is even stronger when it comes to literature - as McKean said, "What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are not as relevant to other arts, like music, but they seem to be just as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values... Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there."

Germany's got this amazing vibe going on right now, it's like a super strong country with its own unique culture that you can feel all the way from the Alps in München down to the Baltic sea city of Kiel.  You can sense it in Köln on the Rhine, in the middle of the country, and even in the Saxon city of Dresden on the Elbe. It's no surprise that Germany's culture is a mix of different sources and tribes, considering how it all came together. 

Germania is basically the ancestral land of the Germans, but where the name actually came from is still up for debate among scholars. Some think it's from a Germanic tribe known as the Tungrians, or even from a previous name for the Germans before they crossed the Rhine and battled the Gauls. Julius Caesar was the first to use the word "Germanus" in his commentary on the Gallic Wars, where he took it from the Gauls themselves to distinguish between the ones he'd conquered and the ones he hadn't. He wrote in his first book, "Germans, who live beyond the Rhine, are always at war with the Gauls. They fight the Germans almost every day." Others believe it might mean "spear" from the Old English word ger, or possibly from the Old Irish word garim, which means "to shout," implying the Germans were super loud. 

The Roman historian Tacitus wrote in his book "De Origine et situ Germanorum" around AD 98 that the Germans were aboriginal and not mixed with other races. He said, "Who would leave Asia or Africa for Italy, let alone Germany, with its harsh climate, gloomy skies, and sullen people?" It's pretty obvious the Romans wouldn't be interested in moving there, at least not yet. They'd send out their conquests to Germania to trade and occasionally lead a land campaign, but they'd mostly stay in their empire. The Germanic tribes started showing up around the first century, living on the Roman Empire's borders, trading their goods and serving in the Roman army.

I stood there staring blankly at the scene before me, my mind a complete blank slate.  I just couldn't seem to grasp anything about it, like it was just a bunch of random stuff I was looking at.  My thoughts were zipping in and out of my brain too fast for me to catch them.  I was like a total robot, just processing the image without really thinking about it.

I had been wanting to learn how to draw for ages, ever since I was six.  Then I got this art book called The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain and it totally changed everything.  It teaches you all these crazy cool techniques like how to break down a picture into simple shapes and stuff.  One trick it shows you is to frame a picture with a square, which makes it way easier to draw.  But at that moment, I was so overwhelmed by the whole thing that I just couldn't even think about framing it.  I was stuck, just staring at the picture in awe.

I've always been fascinated by artists who create masterpieces with crazy styles, like Picasso with his blue phase or Monet with his greenery.  If I wanted to be an artist, I figured this was my chance to make something special – I'd call it Work in Brown.  I picked up my pencil, my hand started moving, and for a second, I felt like I was totally in the zone.  But then I had to go and mess it up by trying to, ahem, take care of a little business...  My hand smacked the toilet handle, but the, um, 'present' refused to budge.  I was stuck staring at this gross brown package that someone had left behind.  I grabbed the mop, frowning, trying to get my mind off the situation.  A few more flushes, a few more minutes of me standing there, then I finally managed to get my hand into the toilet and...well, let's just say it was a real challenge.

Teenage drivers are dying behind the wheel in alarming numbers.  Several factors contribute to this disturbing trend.  According to the National Institutes of Health, a big part of the problem is that the teen brain just isn't ready for the risks of driving.  Inexperience is another major factor – it not only causes more fatal accidents, but also increases the rate of vehicle rollover, speeding, and driving off the road.  And, as anyone can guess, teens often drive with their friends – which is a deadly combo.  A study by the Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center found that the more underage passengers, the higher the risk of traffic accidents.

California and some other states have tried to make teens safer by requiring temporary licenses that limit their driving hours and ban other minors as passengers.  But these provisional licenses are just a temporary fix.  The real issue is that, as a group, teen drivers are just not ready to handle the risks and responsibilities of driving.  Researcher Marvin Zuckerman thinks that 18 is still too young for a regular driver's license, and he's got the stats to back it up.  A common trait among teens is the desire to take risks for the thrill of it, so it makes sense to delay driving until they're a bit older.  If we keep giving out driver's licenses to young teens, we'll just keep seeing deadly accidents happen, and the death toll will skyrocket in the next few years.  By 2010, millions of new teen drivers will hit the road, and the situation could get even more serious.

Legislation to deal with this issue would be pretty straightforward.  Schools could still teach driver's education classes to get future drivers started, but no one under 18 could drive.  A provisional permit could still be issued before a full license, and a certain number of driving hours would still be required.  The number of hours could be based on the number already required in most states (in California, for example, that's 6 hours of behind-the-wheel training and 50 hours of practice with a grown-up).  Uniform national legislation would be a reasonable and effective way to protect teens across the country.  This idea's not new, but it's still worth considering.

So I spent some time browsing through the Library of Congress's film collection and decided to check out the trick films from 1895 to 1901. There were a total of 15 of these films, and I watched them all. Trick films use creative editing to create illusions, so I focused on analyzing the style and evolution of these early films. Most of them are pretty straightforward - they're set-bound, shot in a frontal proscenium, feature no camera movement, and stick to the one shot equals one film rule. However, some of the later films broke free from these rules by introducing new ideas like multiple shots.

One thing that stood out to me was how all the trick films share the same set-up: they're all shot on a static set within a frontal proscenium. The camera stays in one place and doesn't follow the action. This style came from the theatre and, for trick films, the magic shows and vaudeville acts of the time. A big limitation of this style is that the actors can only move side-to-side, they can't walk towards or away from the camera. Check out Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900) for an example - the actors enter from the right and just bop back and forth across the screen.

These films also tend to use a lot of long shots and, occasionally, medium shots. They never use close-ups, just like in the theatre and vaudeville days when the whole performance would be visible on stage. The actors stay in the middle ground and don't move towards the camera, so the audience never gets a close-up shot. Most of these early trick films are pretty short, lasting only a minute or so, because they follow the rule of one conceptual shot equals one film. This limits what they can do, so most of them are just simple tricks like magic or disappearing acts. However, look closer at a film like The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895) and you'll see that the physical shot and the conceptual shot aren't always the same thing - sometimes a single shot is made up of multiple physical shots to create an illusion.

John Taylor from Caroline was super into the idea of Republicanism and was always speaking his mind about personal freedom and government. As a farmer, his job and his short stint in politics made him known for being outspoken and dedicated. His love for the country life influenced just about all his thoughts on government, especially when it came to how a system should work. He thought that preserving and supporting agriculture was the key to making good arguments about things like power, rules, and the courts.

Taylor believed that the United States had a unique chance to create the perfect system because nobody was stuck in the past and telling them what to do. This meant that they could make a system where people had control over themselves. He was all about the natural rights of people, and he thought that they're all connected - if one of them gets taken away, the others get hurt too, and they're not as valuable. He thought that these rights should be off-limits to the government. He said that the "state of nature" was basically a world where the strong and mean people get ahead, but in a civilized society, that's not how it should be.

To make this perfect society, Taylor thought that the government had to be created so that it accounted for both the good and bad in people. He was super strict about his ideas on right and wrong being two separate things. He said that since governments are run by people, they'll have all the good and bad qualities that come with being human. He thought that good principles were about protecting private property, helping farmers, and keeping capitalism in check. He believed that a government with good principles would work fairly no matter who was in charge, even if they were mostly looking out for themselves. He thought that people are self-centered, but that's not always a bad thing - it's only bad when it hurts others. A good government was needed to keep people's bad qualities in check, and it had to be watched closely to make sure it didn't add any bad principles.

Like many other strong Republicans back then, Taylor wanted the government to stick to the Constitution and not do anything that wasn't clearly said in it. He thought that a big government was expensive and likely to be super controlling. However, he also thought that just following the words without thinking about what the writers meant could be really bad. He even thought that the Declaration of Independence was like the true guide for the United States because it made it clear that we're a group of states, not one single country.

Going back to the data in Figure 17, we saw a drastic drop in commuter log entries during the third month of the project. That was pretty discouraging, and it wasn't easy to figure out why it happened. Winter was in full swing at our New England campus, which probably contributed to the decline in bicycle and foot traffic. Also, December signals the end of the fall semester, so people were busy wrapping up schoolwork and finals, and the commuter log might have slipped their minds. To make things worse, it's the start of the holiday season, and students and faculty get a month-long break, which means many people didn't even need to come to campus. As for January, classes resumed in late January, but I'm not sure if that's related to the low log submissions for that month. What really puzzles me, though, is why the submissions remained low in February. Maybe it's just the natural life cycle of a project - everyone gets excited at first, and then things die down. To combat this, we launched the Carpool Challenge Week in March, a special push to reinvigorate the project, which did lead to a surge in log submissions that month. So, we faced the tough challenge of keeping the project going despite a natural dip in interest, compounded by the semester and holiday breaks that come with higher education.

Another hurdle we faced (and any commuting project will, I guess) is that people really love their freedom, independence, and the flexibility of driving. It's a deep-seated part of our culture. To get people to switch to alternative modes of commuting, we needed to offer some serious incentives. We gave out gift cards to local spots, but it would have been cool to see how bigger prizes, like a new bike, a hybrid car, or an electric car, would have affected participation. That might have helped us combat that initial dip in engagement. The prizes we offered didn't change, though - if we had announced some bigger prizes, like a bike in December and a car in January, I bet it would have made a difference.

I just learned about Exchange Traded Funds, or ETFs for short, and they're pretty cool.  They're like index funds but way more flexible and you can buy and sell them like stocks.  You get the good stuff about index funds like diversification, but you also get the benefits of owning individual stocks, like being able to short sell and buy on margin.  Plus, you can buy just one share, which is pretty sweet.  But the best part is that ETFs are way cheaper than the average mutual fund.  The only downside is that you have to pay a commission when you trade them, just like with stocks.  There are tons of different ETFs out there, so it's up to you to figure out which ones are the best.  In this case, we're looking at the ETF IHF and comparing it to its top 10 holdings to see if owning just those stocks is better than owning the whole ETF.  We're only looking at the top 10 because it would be crazy to try to analyze every single holding.  These 10 stocks make up 63.58% of the ETF's assets, so it's a good representation.

To see how well these 10 stocks represent the whole ETF, we're going to use some math to calculate their Beta and Return.  If we had a portfolio made up of just these 10 stocks, how would it compare to the whole ETF?  The chart shows that if we just owned the top 10 stocks, our portfolio would be 16% higher in returns and have a lower Beta than the ETF.  That sounds like a pretty good deal!  But before we get too excited, we need to make sure that these results are actually significant.  To do that, we're going to look at the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks and compare it to the ETF's standard deviation.  If the two are different, then we can say that the results are statistically significant.

Dream-Land is one of Edgar Allan Poe's top poems, and he thought it was his best work. In this poem, you'll find the word "Thulé" popping up in lines 6 and 56 - it was a term that Poe got from Virgil, or so says Mabbott. Virgil used it to refer to an island north of Britain that the Greeks thought was the edge of the known world. However, there's another source that might be responsible for Poe's use of the term. Poe was really into German writers, and one of his favorites was Goethe.

This is important because it shows how familiar Poe was with Goethe's work. Karl J. Arndt, in his book about Poe and Goethe, thinks that Poe copied some of his ideas from Goethe's writing. The Oxford Companion to English Literature says that Goethe was a big deal in the literary world for his poetic drama Faust, which came out in two parts, first in 1808 and again in 1832, the year Goethe died. Inside Faust's second part is a short poem called "The King of Thulé", which is all about a king whose wife dies after giving him a fancy goblet. The king gets super drunk, cries a lot, and decides it's time to die too. He gives away his stuff to his kids, except the goblet, and then walks off a cliff, throws the goblet into the ocean, closes his eyes, and checks out. The King of Thulé is a bit like the king in Dream-Land, maybe even a dark twin of Poe's struggles with loss and drinking. Goethe's Faust was even adapted into a romantic drama by H P Grattan in 1842, just a year before Poe used the term Thule in "The Pit and the Pendulum".

Poe references Thule twice in his writing, once in "The Pit and the Pendulum" and again in "Dream-Land", where he uses it as the opening and closing lines for the poem. "The King of Thulé" and "Dream-Land" are kind of like two poems that go together. In "Dream-Land", the speaker describes Thule as a dark, lonely place where he's haunted by dead friends and sees a world without color. This is similar to how Goethe's king feels after losing his wife - he's all alone, lost his will to live, and is just going through the motions. It's like Poe is stepping into Goethe's poem and describing it from his own perspective.

Goethe was a big deal in the literary world, and Poe would have known about him for sure because of his respect for Tennyson. Poe even said that he admired Tennyson. Poe would've also been exposed to Goethe's work through all the reproductions that were happening after the original publication.

Is it possible that a customer would get punitive damages in court after slipping and falling on an applesauce spill in a grocery store because the manager was eating dinner instead of cleaning up the mess, even though he'd been told twice about it? Probably not, but a judge wouldn't immediately dismiss the claim. To win punitive damages, the customer would have to prove that the manager was being super reckless and didn't care about the harm that could happen, which is called "despicable" in the law. This customer can argue that the manager should have known how bad it would be if he didn't clean up the spill because a bunch of people had already slipped and fallen in the same store just a few months ago, and he still did nothing. It's not a super strong argument, but it makes sense given that six people had slipped and fallen in the store in 2009 and the manager didn't do anything about it. 

On October 13th, an employee told the manager about the spill, but the manager said he was too busy eating dinner to deal with it. Another employee reminded him about 15 minutes later, and he said the same thing. Then, at 5:30 pm, the customer slipped and fell on the spill and got hurt pretty badly. Before that accident, there had been five other slip-and-fall incidents in the same store in 2009. Now the customer is suing the store for money because of her injury and we're thinking about filing a motion to get the court to toss out the part of the lawsuit that wants punitive damages.

In California, you can get punitive damages if someone did something really bad on purpose or was super reckless and didn't care about hurting others. The law says that's called "malice," and it means either intentionally causing harm or doing something super bad that you knew could hurt someone, and then going ahead and doing it anyway. In one case, a court said that's exactly what happened when someone knew something was going to be super bad, but they still chose to do it and hurt someone.

About four years ago, I took a course on Islam at CBC, which got me thinking about a really big question: is Islam a hostile religion?  To be honest, I think this question is more relevant now than ever, especially when you look back at what's happened since 9/11.  From what I've observed, the media's view of Islam has gone from pretty negative to extremely tolerant in the US.  It's crazy to think that back in 2001, a presidential candidate with Islamic ties, like Barack Obama, would have been a total long shot.

The Story of the Prophet really caught my attention.  This biography of Muhammad conflicts with what I thought I knew about him.  I used to think that Muhammad forced people to convert to Islam, but the story presents him as a totally different guy - a humble martyr who was misunderstood and even humbled by others.  People started to see the truth in his teachings and sought him out one by one.  It's weird to see how the biography is written in a way that makes Muhammad seem like a humble prophet who didn't need to prove anything, just live his life and let the miracles speak for themselves.  This kind of writing is actually misleading because it downplays the miracle and life of Jesus Christ.  It's like they're taking credit for Jesus' life and personhood through Muhammad.

I also noticed that the biography tries to show how people converted to Islam on their own, but the stories are all second- or third-hand.  It's like they're trying to prove the truth of the stories, but it makes them seem suspicious.  The thing that really gets me is that they're trying to make Muhammad out to be this perfect guy who's humble, endearing, wise, and gentle, but history says the opposite.  It's hard not to wonder if Muslims today really know the truth behind Muhammad's rise to power.

Christianity's roots and the actual teachings of Jesus got lost in the shuffle as the faith evolved after his death.  If we look at it in big picture terms, we can see how Christianity drifted further and further away from its original ideas.  Nowadays, it seems like there's a growing awareness and a more progressive mindset.  Traditionalists might resist any changes, but they might not be influential enough to hold things back.  As time goes on, people will become more aware of the history of Christianity, and a desire will grow to separate the added stuff from what Jesus really taught.  It might take decades or even centuries, but it's inevitable:  There will be a big reversal in Christianity's history, and it will return to its original form.  A movement will grow, and it'll strip away all the extra layers of doctrine, kind of like the clock turning backward, until all you're left with is Jesus' original message.  When this trend hits the US and Europe, it'll spread like wildfire, and people will start following Jesus' ideas like it's the 1st century all over again.  The church as an institution will still be strong, but because people will be going back to the basics, there'll be more similarity between different groups and regions, rather than differences.  History is full of examples of reversals - just think about how the Roman Empire used to hate Christians, but later they took over the empire.  Our country went from having African-American slaves to having African-American leaders.  The same thing will happen with Christianity, and it'll be a big reversal of history as people search for the source.  It's crucial to interpret Jesus' words as metaphors, not literal statements, for this to happen.  So what's been added to Christianity since Jesus' time?

If we go way back in time, we see only Judaism, the root of the Christian faith.  By the time the Romans took over Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E., monotheism, divinely revealed religion, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures were all part of the Jewish faith.  But the Jewish people weren't a single unit - they were divided into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and the majority of common folk.

I think The Jungle really shows the darker side of human nature. People, deep down, are super selfish and only care about themselves. They just want to live the best life possible and don't worry about anyone else. The Jungle shows this in lots of ways. The owners and bosses of the big factories are the most obvious example. All they care about is making their companies huge and awesome, no matter who gets hurt or what gets in their way. They don't care about the pollution they're creating or the animals and people getting hurt because of it. Upton Sinclair does a great job of painting a picture of how bad it is with his words, like when he says, "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world". He's showing how much damage they're causing and how the owners don't care about anyone or anything getting hurt. They're just all about the money.

The bosses and owners also didn't care about their workers who were making them rich. They would do anything to save a buck, like, "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar". They made their workers work super long hours and then would lay off huge groups of people without any warning or help. Back then, there weren't many laws to protect workers' safety or well-being, so the bosses and owners were basically in charge and could do whatever they wanted. They expected the workers to just deal with the terrible conditions they were living and working in, and there were no organizations to help them. The unions that formed were more of a problem because they made money off the workers. It was like the workers were slaves, "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery".

A lot of authors are really good at making readers feel a certain way about important topics. They use different techniques to do this, but some are way more effective than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald is a master at this in his novel The Great Gatsby. Sometimes, he pairs up words that don't usually go together to give readers a certain vibe about a subject. Other times, he gives a symbol meaning and then uses it for the same thing. Fitzgerald does this with lots of colors, like gold, green, white, gray, red, and pink. In The Great Gatsby, he builds up meaning for some of these colors, like white and gray, and then uses that meaning to make readers feel a certain way about important objects.

Fitzgerald uses the technique of giving meaning to colors and then using them to make readers feel something in a big way with white and gray. He makes white mean something fancy and high class, while gray is more old and faded. He sets this up at the start of the novel by using both colors all the time. Everyone's always wearing white - Daisy and Jordan are "in white" all the time (8), and even guys like Nick and Tom are wearing white too: Nick's got "white flannels" (41) for Gatsby's party, and Tom's wearing a "white shirt" (36) when he meets Myrtle. Even Catherine is "powdered milky white" (30). The only time people aren't wearing white is when Nick's describing Gatsby's party, and the halls are "gaudy with primary colors" (40). Fitzgerald takes it to the next level by using these colors to describe boring, everyday things: Nick goes "down the white chasms of lower New York" (56) on his way to work, and the names of people at Gatsby's parties are now "gray names" (61) on Nick's timetable. He even describes ordinary people and places as white or gray: Jordan and Daisy had a "white girlhood" (19) together, there are "gray cars" and "gray land" (23) in the valley of ashes, the "Italian child" in the railroad is "gray" (26), and the dog-seller is "a gray old man" (27). After Fitzgerald gets this meaning across, he uses white and gray to make readers see certain subjects as unimportant or just part of a crowd. This starts with Daisy. After a while without using these colors, Fitzgerald describes Daisy as "dressed in white" in a "little white roadster" (74), and readers start to see her as just a uniform thing that Gatsby wants and longs for. He uses more of this technique around Daisy to make her seem like just a uniform addition, for example, there's a "gray haze of Daisy's fur collar" (18), and she's again in a "white" (115) dress before Tom and Gatsby's encounter.

San Diego County is a super productive agricultural hotspot thanks to its amazing climate. It's all sunshine and mild vibes here. You can grow all sorts of tasty crops like tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, peaches, lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There's a huge demand for organic, community-supported agriculture food in the area, with many local groups having crazy long waiting lists. People are totally into organic eggs and milk too. Some of these organic farms even offer tours, hiking trails, and birdwatching spots, which is a win-win for the landowner and the environment. This kind of setup lets them tap into government programs that benefit both the farmer and the wildlife. It's like killing two birds with one stone.

Organic farming has its perks, like a more diverse range of plants and wildlife in the area because there are no yucky chemicals in the soil and water. However, it's not all sunshine and rainbows. Organic farming can be way more labor-intensive and costly than conventional farming. You have to spend more time and effort removing pests and weeds and fertilizing the soil without using harsh chemicals. And, let's be real, organic farms often have higher losses and are way less efficient than big commercial operations. On top of that, some beneficial practices that help wildlife, like planting cover crops and removing invasive species, can be super time-consuming and costly. So, it's no wonder the landowner in this scenario might be looking for some financial help or expert advice to maximize both their profits and wildlife-friendly practices.

The land I'm talking about is a 160-acre plot near the town of Potrero in unincorporated San Diego County, California. It's a mix of chaparral, nonnative grassland, and oak woodland right next to the Cleveland National Forest. This land is in the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion, which is part of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. The plan is still a work in progress, but it currently covers over a hundred plant and animal species, including some that are super rare and endangered, like the Stephens' kangaroo rat, the mountain yellow-legged frog, and the California gnatcatcher. Others are declining and might be listed as endangered soon, like the burrowing owl.

This land has been home to Native Americans for centuries and was later settled by cattle ranchers and wood sellers in the late 1800s. It was part of an original homestead patent, so it was probably used for grazing and wood production for a while. I chose this piece of land from a real estate website and did some research on government programs that might help a small farmer like this one reduce costs and maintain wildlife-friendly practices. I even found an organic farm in the same area that I used as a model for what this landowner might try to achieve.

When it comes to negotiation, culture plays a huge role. Culture isn't something that can be defined by just a few words, and it's not a one-size-fits-all kind of thing. It's the opposite of what you might think it is, and it's often different from what you might expect. For example, saying "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are super accommodating" is way too broad and doesn't really capture the full picture. What's more helpful to a negotiator is understanding what a culture's values and attitudes are, and how they might impact the negotiation. When you're dealing with a culture that's different from your own, you end up comparing it to your own culture, and that's when things can get pretty relatable. 

Trying to understand a foreign culture or mindset can be a real challenge. It might involve studying its history or figuring out its biases. Instead of judging or trying to change a culture, you should just accept it for what it is and work with it, especially when you're in a tough bargaining position. And even if you're the one who's visiting someone else's turf, showing respect for their traditions and values can really help you get past any cultural barriers and move the negotiation forward.

But here's the thing: culture isn't just about national differences. Even within the same country, companies can have their own unique corporate cultures. For example, some companies might value long hours in the office, while others are way more relaxed. You can see evidence of this in things like dress codes, communication styles, and hiring practices. And let me tell you, American corporate culture is all over the map - some companies are super formal, while others are super casual. It's like you need to dig deeper to really understand what's going on.

Values are even more important to get a handle on, because they're like the underlying reason why a culture is the way it is. If a culture values things like saving face or communal harmony, you can bet that a negotiator from that culture won't be willing to publicly shame their company or their boss to get a good deal. On the other hand, if a culture values getting a hard bargain, you won't see the negotiator settling for anything less than the best deal possible. So, it's really helpful to consider these kinds of things before you sit down at the negotiation table. And, if you can, it's even better to get to know your opponent on a personal level - it can really make the negotiation go more smoothly.

The quote 'There is no God' isn't a phrase you'd hear from St. Anselm or St. Thomas Aquinas. That's a line from Psalm 14 in the Christian Bible, and it's where Anselm starts his argument for the existence of God. This belief is also shared by Thomas Aquinas. Since their arguments are both in defense of the same concept of God, we'll assume they're both right, and we'll compare them later. To keep things simple, we'll only talk about their arguments for the God of the Bible. If we were to consider other types of gods, it wouldn't let us fairly compare their ideas. 

For the sake of simplicity, let's assume both Anselm and Aquinas are correct in their belief in God. We'll show that, even though they bring up valid points, neither of them provides a complete basis for believing in God.

To get started, let's look at Anselm's argument. He thinks you can find proof of God by looking within yourself. He claims that because we can imagine God, we can't imagine that he doesn't exist. His idea is hard to put into words, but basically, he says that proof for God is already inside our minds. He thinks we don't need to look outside ourselves for the truth about God; we just need to think about what we already know is true. This idea of trusting in something without concrete evidence is, in Christian texts, called faith.

Anselm's idea is different from Aquinas's. Aquinas thinks you can prove the existence of God using logic and facts, without needing any faith. This would be helpful in spreading Christianity, because new followers wouldn't need to accept something they can't prove. They could be convinced by logic alone. Aquinas uses five different logical arguments to prove God's existence: change, causation, being in a state of uncertainty, degrees of excellence, and how things fit together. In each one, he's saying that God must exist because it makes sense logically. Imagine you're trying to complete a puzzle, and someone tells you that you're missing one piece. You can figure out what the missing piece looks like just by looking at the rest of the puzzle.

So, I'm learning about ancient times – like, a really long time ago, over 2,500 years ago. It was around the fifth or sixth century BCE, and a dude who would eventually be called Buddha was born. This guy renounced the world, became enlightened, and started teaching his ideas, which eventually led to the creation of Buddhism, specifically the Theravada branch. If you think back to when Buddha was alive, it was definitely different from how it is now. For instance, Sri Lanka has this super old tradition where they celebrate this water-cutting ceremony, but Buddha never actually taught about anything like that. It's pretty cool how the religion has changed over time – not just some superficial stuff, but also the core ideas that Buddhism is built on.

There are some important terms that I'll be using a lot in this discussion. When I say internal, I mean something that's inside the Buddhist community – like, it's not from outsiders, but from people who are actually a part of it. External means something that's coming from outside the community. Hostile means it's trying to hurt the community, even if it's not necessarily a bad thing. And benign means it's not trying to harm or help the community, even if it accidentally does one or the other. These terms will show up a lot.

First off, I need to break down the basics of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists believe in this thing called the Triple Gem – it's like the Buddha, the teachings (Dhamma), and the community (Sangha). The Dhamma is basically the Buddhist texts, which are divided into three groups. The Sutta Pitaka has the sayings of Buddha, the Vinaya Pitaka has rules for living, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka has the deeper stuff about the meaning of life, like no soul (Anatta), suffering (Dukkha), and how everything is temporary (Anicca). If you understand these ideas, you can stop going through this cycle of death and rebirth (Sansara), and you can also get rid of desire (lobha), hatred (dosa), and delusion (moha). The Vinaya Pitaka also gives rules for monks and laypeople, like the five precepts (no killing, lying, stealing, misbehaving, or getting drunk). Monks have way more rules to follow. One of the most important ideas in Buddhism is the Four Noble Truths: life is suffering (Dukkha), attachment causes suffering, and suffering can be overcome.

The US and Mexico are like two countries that used to hate each other for a super long time - 57 whole years (Diehl and Goerts 2000, p. 145). The worst part of their rivalry was the Mexican-American War from 1846 to 1848 when the US basically defeated Mexico and took Texas and the American Southwest (Schmitt 1974 p. 30-31). They had a bunch of other clashes too, but it all finally settled down just before World War I. I guess it's like what happens when two neighbors can't agree on stuff. It's the same with lots of countries who have a border with another country - they often disagree on big things like money, culture, and stuff (Schmitt 1974 p. 30-31).

It's not like the US and Mexico are the only ones with a long-standing rivalry - lots of countries with a shared border have similar problems. David M. Pletcher (1977) said that Mexico and Cuba are the only countries where the US has super long-standing diplomatic issues (p. 41). I guess it's because they're close to the US and have been at odds with it for a while. Other countries in Latin America have gotten along pretty well with the US.

It turns out that the US and Mexico didn't get along because of some pretty deep-seated issues - it's like they had a major disagreement about what to believe in. Sally Frahm (2001) said that back in the day, Americans were super opposed to Catholicism and monarchy (p. 86). It's kinda like how the US and the Soviet Union didn't get along during the Cold War - they had some big ideological differences. But with the US and Mexico, it was more about their different religions. This whole thing started because the US and Mexico inherited some bad feelings from their former colonial rulers (the English and Spanish).

Diehl and Goerts (2000) counted 17 times when the US and Mexico disagreed over 57 years. Most of these disagreements were about border stuff, like when Mexican bandits would cross over into the US, or when American outlaws would cause trouble in Mexico (Schmitt 1974 p. 97). It wasn't until the US and Mexico both started cracking down on their borders that things started to get better.

Schmitt (1974) said that things started to calm down when Mexico realized it needed the US a lot more (p. 109), and the US stopped trying to expand its territory and started focusing on helping Mexico out financially (p. 110).

It's been 15 years since an illness I never even knew existed suddenly turned my life upside down and left me disabled. I was 46 at the time, working as a nurse, and had chosen the profession to escape feelings of uncertainty from my childhood. I was constantly told, "You'll always be able to find work; people will always get sick," but that didn't live up to reality. As a result, I've been living on Social Security Disability for 15 years, and to be honest, I'm still struggling every day. What keeps me going is the unwavering support of my family and a few close friends - I'm not as strong as I thought I was when disaster struck. 

My point is that no matter how prepared we think we are, life can still throw us curveballs. There are no guarantees, and when the going gets tough, people need each other's help. I agree that we should question our reliance on the government, but instead of building our own shelters, we should be learning to trust and support each other. The idea of rugged individualism that Conservatives talk about isn't entirely accurate - the pioneers who settled the West didn't do it alone; they relied on each other for survival. 

While being prepared is a good idea, it's just as essential to build relationships with the people around us. I've got my emergency kit ready, complete with first aid supplies, water purification tablets, and all the essentials, but I also know that having neighbors who care can make all the difference. If you have the resources, it's great to have a small farm and a wood stove, but what's most important is knowing the people who live next door.

So, what drives organisms to evolve in the way they do? Are there any roadblocks or restrictions that influence the direction of evolutionary change? Even back in 1917, D'Arcy Thompson said it was like trying to put into mathematical terms even the simplest living things. Fast forward to now, and we're still scratching our heads - but, we've been using math to help us understand certain parts of mollusk shell development through both how they grow and how they evolved over time (think Raup and Stanley's work from 1981 as an example). Our project is all about using mathematical modeling of how Prunum develops over time and in its history, combined with some actual experiments, to figure out what's behind the direction and strength of evolutionary changes. We used X-rays of Prunum species to pick out some key stats that we could then use to model different possible and real shell shapes. These numbers got plugged into a computer program called CerioShell (Stone, 1995), and we used it to imagine what shell shapes could be possible. This stuff is being combined with other studies to get a better handle on what's going on in the history of this group of animals.

Think of a shell like a tube that's constantly moving through space over time - it's kind of like a journey that's 360 degrees long. The parts of the shell that twist around in a spiral pattern are called whorls, and they're all connected by a line that runs through the center of the shell, called the columella. The speed at which these whorls get bigger can vary, and each one is separated by a line called a suture. In most shells, the biggest whorl is the last one (that's the body whorl). The spire is all the whorls except the last one, and the tip of the spire is the apex, while the other end is the base. The animal pops out of its shell through an opening called the aperture.

We can look at shells in different ways, like from the front, back, opening, or from the side that's opposite the opening. Usually, when we look at a shell, it's from the front, with the opening facing us and the pointy end pointing up.

Here's a cool way to count the whorls: first, look at the shell from the front, then find where the first line between two whorls starts. Draw a line between them, and count the whorls from that line - you can even estimate to a quarter of a whorl if you need to.

A shell can also be thought of like a bunch of openings that move through space and time as the animal builds its shell. You can actually track the path of the opening by looking at the center of each whorl's opening, and the horizontal and vertical distance from the center to the edge of the opening. This path can be shown on a graph or mathematically. Once we have the math formula, we can play around with different parameters and see how they affect how the mollusk builds its shell.

I've been going over the facts about neonatal and infant mortality in Indonesia, and it's been a real bummer to see that there hasn't been a lot of change in the past ten years.  They're doing okay with some of the Millennium Development Goals, like getting people clean water and a decent bathroom, but when it comes to how well they're doing on child and mom health stuff, they're way behind where they need to be to meet their goals by 2015.  There are a lot of reasons for this, which I'll get into below, and it's pretty clear that they need to beef up their health system instead of just focusing on one-off programs.
	First off, Indonesia has made some progress with getting more births where a trained health worker is present, but 72% still means that a lot of moms aren't getting the help they need if something goes wrong.  It's like, yeah, more people are getting this, but it's not like it's a guarantee they'll get the care they need.  Plus, the ones who are trained are often just traditional workers, like midwives, who can't handle emergencies.  You can bet that a lot of the deaths are because of things like bleeding during pregnancy, which is a big problem.  So, even though they're getting better at this one thing, there's still lots to work on.  Another area that's a concern is how many kids with diarrhea under five are actually getting help from a health pro, and it's pretty low across the whole country.  They also don't have much data on how well new moms are doing after they give birth, but it's clear that's an issue too.
	When it comes to C-sections, they're not happening often enough - only about 4% of births are C-sections.  But what's even more worrying is that the rate is way lower in rural areas, at only 2%.  This shows that people in the cities are getting way more access to healthcare than those in the sticks.  It's like they're leaving the poor people behind.  And it gets even worse when you look at how well people in different income groups are using healthcare services - there's a huge gap between the richest and poorest people, and it's almost like they can't afford it.  Clearly, people have to pay out of pocket for healthcare, which is a real problem. 
	Now, when it comes to figuring out how to fix all this, the main question is whether Indonesia should focus on specific programs or fix the whole health system at once.  On the one hand, targeting one area of healthcare sounds good because it's like, hey, let's get this one thing done and be done with it.  But the problem is that when you put all your eggs in one basket, other areas suffer and people start working on that one thing instead of other important stuff.  Just look at what happened with HIV/AIDS funding - it totally took resources away from family planning.  Plus, having lots of programs going on at the same time just means you end up with a bunch of duplicated and uncoordinated services, which makes it harder to get things done.

Victorian novels are super detailed and often focus on the aristocracy of that time period, but there are two novels that stand out for not following this pattern - Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights.  Both of these novels have a mysterious vibe and a bit of the weird and unusual, which is pretty different from the norm for the Victorian era. This adds depth to the characters and lets us see into their thoughts and feelings. They're not just rich people, they're real people with their own problems and emotions.

I was totally confused, like I was walking around with Sikes and Crackit, who were arguing, and I could hear what they were saying. When I snapped back to reality, I was talking to them, but I didn't know what was going on. Suddenly, loud noises and flashes of light hit me, and I felt like I was being pulled around by some invisible force. It was all a bit fuzzy, but I could feel this gnawing pain that wouldn't go away.

 In these two novels, mystery often shows up in dream sequences or dream-like moments, but it's used in different ways. In Oliver Twist, these strange happenings often reveal what's going on inside Oliver's head, what's bothering him, and what he knows about the world around him. When Oliver gets shot in chapter 28, it's like he's reliving it in a dream, as he tries to find help. The scene shows how little control Oliver had over the events unfolding around him, and how desperate he was, as shown through his hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit. The shooting overwhelms him, and all his senses are numb; he doesn't notice the force that's taking him away, and he feels his fear and pain all over again, but without the shock. This makes us wonder whose fault it is that Oliver's in this situation, since it's definitely not his own. This scene also implies that Oliver's giving up, like he's been broken by Fagin and is just accepting his fate, which affects his ability to make decisions. Otherwise, we'd expect him to try to take action, even if it's just to save himself.

The day passed by so quickly, like it was just a blur. I mean, it was gone as soon as it started, and then night came back around again - it was so long and silent, but also so short and fleeting.

It's been a couple of years since I worked at an after-school program helping elementary students with their studies, but one kid in particular stuck in my mind. I was assigned to help a little boy named Adrian, who was really struggling with reading. I soon realized something was off; he could pronounce some of the letters perfectly, but others were a complete mystery. It was a weird situation, especially since he spoke perfect English - or so I thought, until I met his mom. She didn't speak a word of English, only Spanish, and I was struggling to communicate with her, my Spanish skills being pretty basic. It hit me like a ton of bricks when I realized Adrian was actually reading just fine, but he just didn't know the English alphabet that well. I'm not sure if this revelation made a big difference in his reading, but I hope he's doing okay now.

I share this story to highlight the issue of language barriers in schools, especially here in California. It's not as straightforward as we think; even kids who speak perfect English can still struggle with reading. I'm sure everyone agrees that this is a problem, so what's the solution? For Adrian, the answer was simple: extra help with the English alphabet and pronunciation. But for kids who barely speak English, it's much more complicated. There's no one-size-fits-all solution. The dual language system, mainstream immersion, private tutors, ESL classes - none of these things on their own will fix the problem. The key is to combine them all.

First off, the dual language system is a great idea that benefits not just kids who speak Spanish at home, but all kids. Studies have shown that kids in two-way bilingual education programs perform better academically. There's a lot of fear surrounding this idea, that it's a waste of resources and that most kids won't benefit. But that's just not true. If we implemented these programs in every classroom, all kids would benefit. So, how do we make it happen? Do we require all teachers to be bilingual? That's unrealistic and unfair. But we could definitely have bilingual aids, tutors, or whatever you want to call them, to support our teachers and students.

Most of us learn from a young age that there's something greater than ourselves out there, something that's hard to fully comprehend.  Some people go to church, temple, or find their own inner answers.  Many accept the faith passed down from our parents, while others reject it and think there's nothing beyond our own understanding.  We might start with one set of values, only to change our minds later and adopt another.  Whatever path we take, we're on a journey to figure out who we are through our own unique take on spirituality.  We're searching for a guiding light to lead us out of the darkness.

My dad told me his favorite bird was cardinals when I asked him.  We were sitting on the porch, listening to the rain pound on the tin roof while we smoked our cigarettes.  The rain pouring down was drowning the plants along the edge of the porch.  He looked out into the rain, like he was half thinking, half remembering something.  He'd lost weight and his clothes hung loose on him.  His hair had gotten thinner, too.  He kept staring at the rain, avoiding eye contact.  I felt scared, alone, and didn't know how to talk to him about how much I'd miss him without making it feel more real for both of us.  I hugged him, sat back down, and joined him in staring out into the rain during that June twilight.

My dad passed away in December, just five days after my twenty-second birthday.  The chemo and radiation had only prolonged his suffering; I couldn't figure out what the point of that was.  If there was a God, I wondered, had he stopped listening to me a long time ago?  I said no prayers that night, alone in the darkness. 

I didn't want to watch him die.  I didn't want to see my creator slip away.  I wanted to remember my dad for how he lived, not how he died.  I knew my dad better than anyone else, better than his family.  I knew he wouldn't have wanted me to watch him go.  I curled up in a ball in my bed for three days, waiting for the news.

No one even called me.

The term "Gothic Novel" is basically a contradiction in terms, as Ian Watt described it in The Rise of the Gothic Novel - "an oxymoron for 'Old-New'." The Gothic genre's been getting a bad rap, but it's also been praised for evoking the 'terrible sublime.' People have accused it of being shallow, but others have argued that it's actually pretty deep. The very first "Gothic Novel," Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, took elements from old romances and modern novels and mashed them together to create something entirely new. Walpole called it "A Gothic Story" and it was a game-changer in terms of literary expression. The Gothic genre is all about throwing back to medieval theatre, architecture, and traditions. At the time The Castle of Otranto came out, the word "gothic" was already being used to describe a bunch of different things - people, styles, and time periods. It was seen as outdated and unsophisticated compared to the modern world. But the combination of Gothic flair and the new way novels were written (giving readers a more personal look at the characters' psyches) is what's kept the Gothic genre around for so long and made it both old and new to readers.

One of the most important Gothic ideas in these novels is the concept of chivalry. The medieval idea of chivalry, which involves training a proper knight, is both carried over and altered in The Castle of Otranto. Chivalry is a big deal for Gothic writers because it represents the ideal knight - brave, honorable, and competent - and they saw a lack of that ideal in their own society. Through chivalric concepts and manners, the Gothic past gets idealized and romanticized (which hints at the future evolution of Gothic to Romantic). Walpole wrote The Castle of Otranto during a time of political turmoil and was worried about the future. He thought that the supposed morality and goodness of the Gothic era had been lost in his own society. This idea is clear in characters like Frederic. When we meet him, he's already shown to embody many chivalric traits - he's a prince, he's been through tragedy, and he's supposed to have been killed by infidels. The image of the gallant and courteous knight is exaggerated, which brings the Gothic trope of excess into play.

Supply chain management is like a crazy rollercoaster of goods moving from the customer's order to raw materials, production, and finally to the customer's hands. It all started back in 1982 when Keith Oliver, a super cool consultant, came up with the term supply chain management. He basically described the entire process of planning, implementing, and controlling the supply chain to satisfy customers quickly and efficiently. It's like a puzzle with six key pieces: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. These six elements work together to give customers the best service ever.

Okay, let's dive into the first piece of the puzzle: production. It's like the foundation of the whole supply chain thing. Production is where everything starts, and it's all about figuring out when, why, where, and how to produce the goods. Managers need to know what customers want, and they can find out by checking out the market. The market is like the ultimate indicator of what customers are looking for. Once they've analyzed the market and understand customer demand, they're ready to decide what products to produce, how many to make, and where to make them. They've got to consider customer satisfaction and demand, or it's gonna be a disaster.

For example, when I used to work at Wal-Mart and Target, they had these super detailed booklets and processes for everything from employee uniforms to receiving shipments from trucks. It was like a well-oiled machine, and it helped them work smoothly without any confusion. 

The second key element is supply. It's all about making strategic decisions that determine what a company can do and who they can partner with. A company might have multiple divisions for a single product, each with its own equipment, workers, and specialties. Managers need to decide which division is best for each process, or they might outsource the work to other companies to save money and increase flexibility. The goal is to create velocity – providing quality, flexibility, and low costs all at the same time.
